<h2>It Takes All Kinds</h2>
<p>
  If you have heard the old saying "it takes all kinds to make the world go 'round," then you know what this principle is about. Designing for those unlike yourself depends on the practices of empathy and sympathy. Practicing these means creating designs that will work for the participant. To understand the difference, lets break them down.
</p>
<p>
  The word “empathy” is often used in the design circles to describe an ideal emotional state between designer and partcipant in which the designer has so deeply learned about the participant that they can, as nearly as possible, stand the shoes of
  the partcipant themselves. Operating at a high level, empathy can and should be practiced in tandem with a more targeted sense of sympathy. Sympathy, the ability to feel a similar emotion to another person, allows designers to make a cognitive leap
  across experiences so that they can design for the participants wholly different from themselves. Keeping these two types of emotional intelligence in mind during the Design phase allows designers to create solutions for people whose experiences they
  will never have, but with whom they can empathize at a high level and with whose experiences they can sympathize.
</p>
<p>
  You have practiced this throughout the Discovery phase. As you move deeper into design, remember that deep empathy or sympathy you developed. Lean on that while you iterate in order to design for your particpants, even if they are widely different from yourself.
</p>
